revision.text: ==English== ===Alternative forms=== * {{l|en|ichosen}} ===Etymology=== From {{inh|en|enm|ichosen}}, {{m|enm|ȝechosen}}, for earlier {{m|enm|ȝecoren||chosen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|ġecoren||chosen}}, past participle of {{m|ang|ċēosan||to choose}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|y|chosen}}. More at {{l|en|choose}}. ===Verb=== {{head|en|verb form}} # {{form of|en|Archaic or obsolete form|chosen}}. #* '''1830''', The British magazine: #*: Ye cannot lay one finger upon us to our despite," replied the former, "if my Master permit not; for the race is neither to the swift nor the battle to the strong; for God hath '''ychosen''' ye foolish things of this world to confound ye wise; [...] ====Usage notes==== * Used as a deliberate archaicism in Modern and Early Modern English.
